Section 2: Understanding the Enterprise Context

(Lens for all the manual’s guidance)

2.1. Characteristics of Large Enterprises
	•	Scale: many teams, multiple products, legacy systems, overlapping responsibilities
	•	Legacy architecture, technical debt, coupling, deprecated interfaces
	•	Audit, compliance, regulatory constraints, documentation demand
	•	Siloed organizations, slow decision cycles, multiple approval layers
	•	Political sensitivity, shifting priorities driven by leadership, not engineering

Delivery Implication: You must design governance, buffers, traceability, and visibility — because the environment is not forgiving of opacity.

From the Field: “In one client, a regulatory audit demanded logging of every user action; our system lacked audit hooks. Overnight we had to retrofit instrumentation — cost, schedule, credibility all strained.”

⸻

2.2. Power & Decision Asymmetry
	•	Customers often control funding, sign-off, and change governance; delivery must influence, not dominate
	•	The “blame center” is often on delivery, even when decisions are upstream
	•	Internal politics: stakeholder factions, shifting sponsors, reorganizations

Delivery Implication: Establish documented decision logs, traceability, and escalation paths. Never proceed on verbal consensus.

VP Insight: “When decisions live in email threads, accountability evaporates. Always force a record so no one can accuse you of ‘not agreeing’ later.”

⸻

2.3. Ambiguity, Hidden Dependencies & Unseen Costs
	•	Requirements rarely fully specified — many integration, data, UI, permission, edge cases unknown
	•	Dependencies on external teams, legacy systems, external vendors, or infrastructure readiness
	•	Unforeseen costs: mapping data, schema migrations, security constraints

Delivery Implication: Always assess for unknowns, charge risk buffers, log “unknowns discovered” items.

Caution: The biggest overruns come not from features, but from emergent dependencies you didn’t foresee.

⸻

2.4. Organizational Momentum & Inertia
	•	Business organizations resist change — they have existing processes, stakeholder habits, inertia
	•	Introducing new processes or tools often faces passive resistance
	•	Delivery proposals that challenge established norms must be rational and gentle

Delivery Implication: Start small, deliver quick wins, use champions, emphasize benefits rather than imposition.

Pro Tip: Don’t expect everyone to buy in at day one. Use pilot modules and visibility to scale adoption.

⸻

2.5. Agile Intent vs. Waterfall Expectation
	•	Stakeholders often expect fixed deliverables, dates, resource allocations (waterfall mindset)
	•	They may judge progress by milestone checkboxes, not incremental deliverables
	•	Delivery teams favor flexibility and adaptation

Delivery Implication: You must translate agile increments into stake-holder understandable milestones. Show value early and often.

Why This Matters: A sprint backlog that never maps to stakeholder milestones becomes invisible; you’ll lose influence.

⸻

2.6. Technical Debt & Architectural Constraints
	•	Legacy technical debt constrains velocity
	•	Monolithic systems, tight coupling, lack of modularity cause ripple effect
	•	Upgrades, scalability, performance constraints often neglected until late

Delivery Implication: Treat technical debt as a first-class concern; factor it in backlog and capacity.

From the Field: “We once estimated a simple feature only to find 30% of hours eaten by plumbing legacy hooks — debt had hidden cost.”

⸻

2.7. Resistance to Platform / Tool Adoption
	•	Customer organizations often have entrenched tools, reluctance to adopt new ones
	•	Shadow tooling, manual spreadsheets, silos of knowledge
	•	Governance compliance may prefer known tools

Delivery Implication: Be pragmatic in tool choices. Build bridges; integrate with existing tools when possible.

VP Insight: “Your team is also a customer. The hardest stance is forcing new tools — start with what works.”

